  "explanation": [
    {
      "heading": "What is a Load Balancer?",
      "body": "A load balancer sits between clients and your servers, distributing incoming requests so no single server gets overwhelmed.\n\nWithout one, all traffic hits one machine — your system is as reliable as that single point of failure.",
      "appearsAtStep": 0
    },
    {
      "heading": "Round Robin — Simple and Fair",
      "body": "The simplest algorithm: each new request goes to the next server in a circular sequence.\n\n**Request 1 → S1, Request 2 → S2, Request 3 → S3, Request 4 → S1…**\n\nNo state needed. Works great when all requests are similar in cost.",
      "appearsAtStep": 1,
      "callout": "Round Robin ignores server load — it doesn't know if S1 is stuck processing a slow request."
    },
    {
      "heading": "Least Connections — Smarter Routing",
      "body": "Track how many active connections each server has. Route the next request to the server with the **fewest active connections**.\n\nBetter for scenarios where request processing times vary significantly (e.g., fast DB reads vs slow file uploads).",
      "appearsAtStep": 5
    },
    {
      "heading": "Fault Tolerance — Handling Server Failure",
      "body": "Load balancers run **health checks** (ping each server every few seconds). If a server fails, the LB stops routing to it.\n\nRequests are redistributed to the remaining healthy servers. Users experience a brief slowdown but no outage.",
      "appearsAtStep": 6,
      "callout": "This is why production systems run at least 3 servers — N-1 redundancy means one server can always fail safely."
    },
    {
      "heading": "Weighted Round Robin",
      "body": "Assign a **weight** to each server proportional to its capacity. A server with weight 2 gets twice as many requests as one with weight 1.\n\nUse this when servers have different hardware specs — no reason to treat a 32-core machine the same as an 8-core one.",
      "appearsAtStep": 8
    },
    {
      "heading": "Traffic Spikes — Scaling Out",
      "body": "When all servers are overloaded, the load balancer can't help by itself. Solutions:\n- **Horizontal scaling**: spin up more servers (auto-scaling groups in AWS, GKE, etc.)\n- **Rate limiting**: reject or queue excess requests\n- **Circuit breaker**: return a fast error to clients rather than queuing forever",
      "appearsAtStep": 9
    }
  ],

